hnology is increasing, and slowly, humans are democratising deep-sea exploration, science and science communication. Telepresence and low-cost technologies are allowing many subsets of the global population that previously did not have access to the deep sea in order to be part of the conversation.\n\n01:03:28 \n‘Three Proposals of Understanding All We Need to Change in Us to Become the Sea’ \nJulieta Aranda, Chus Martínez, Ingo Niermann\n\nA conversation led by the expedition leader and two of the expedition participants discussing how the complexities of environmental narratives inform their artistic production and the human process at large.\n\n01:26:10\n‘Everybody Got a Little Voice to Address the Seas’\nChristina Samoka Eu Tony, Reverend Rogers\n\nThis lecture by Christina Samoka Eu Tony and Reverend Rogers provides an insight into the journey of resistance of deep-sea mining in Papua New Guinea. The talk touches on the experimental state of seabed mining technology and the impacts it has on the health of the environment and the country’s population at large.	\N	1	1	1	\N	\N	EN	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of the participant(s) and TBA21–Academy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	The Waves of the Oh!s and the Ah!s	\N	\N	\N	Ocean Space, Church of San Lorenzo, Venice, Italy	{"Diva Amon","Julieta Aranda","Chus Martínez","Ingo Niermann","Reverend Rogers","Christina Samoka Eu Tony"}	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	https://ocean-archive.org/collection/2	\N	\N	t	\N
