finity, perhaps evolved in response to the extreme selection pressures of those times. We here name it Brunaspis enigmatica, and suggest that its irregular deformation is the result of predation by shell-crushing ray-fish, teeth of which have been found in the same stratum.	\N	1	0	1	\N	\N	EN	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of Anne-Sophie Milon and Jan Zalasiewicz	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Society of Ancient Phenomena	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	https://ocean-archive.org/collection/7	\N	\N	t	\N
