was returned to them for the first time after being looted in the scientific raid of Captain Cook in 1769. It is in the context of this political agency that the whale is a sign, that from the tragic legacy of colonialism, new Taonga can be made. This is part of healing the colonial wound, and it is the wounds deep on Te Haa Kui o Tangaroa’s body that the viewer witnesses as Jody Toroa tells her story.	\N	1	1	0	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Ocean Space, Church of San Lorenzo, Venice, Italy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of Khadija von Zinnenburg Carroll and TBA21–Academy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	https://ocean-archive.org/collection/15	\N	\N	t	\N
