534	private/eu-central-1:12102e0b-bb96-42f0-9d3c-1df78ee120b2/418b7876-0b02-4d53-b0c4-38683f95c14b/2bf09240-15e2-11ea-b700-d971786533fd-OceanCallingBehind theScenesphotoshoot_LauraAnderson Barbata_TBA21.mp4	8c9bbd601394d8cb0e2778cc2d2eca71d0a3e03c8ad82f291241295f63550bb1af4d0b56997dcebd303dca415add2026b2f72e60485756796162b65e0d3ae868	\N	\N	24c9255a975e277fcdc89b5d4d22b3f4	\N	2019-12-04 02:33:21.273419+11	2020-01-10 23:15:16.393+11	\N	t	{24,29,3}	{4,26,28,170,176,400,1231,1232,1265,208}	\N	{US}	Video	Artwork Documentation	{"Laura Anderson Barbata",TBA21–Academy}	418b7876-0b02-4d53-b0c4-38683f95c14b	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2017	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	CC BY-NC	Behind the Scenes from 'Ocean Calling' (2017)	\N	\N	A behind the scenes video of the photoshoot for 'Ocean Calling' (2017) by Laura Anderson Barbata in collaboration with Chris Walker and The Brooklyn Jumbies.\n\nCommissioned by TBA21–Academy for World Ocean Day 2017, ‘Ocean Calling’ (2017) charts the physical and emotional relationship to life in our ocean and the urgent need for collective transformation. Anderson Barbata's performative piece embodies her first-hand experiences and research into ancient wisdom whilst on expedition in Papua New Guinea with TBA21–Academy. The resulting work combines spoken word, dance, improvisation, stilt dancing, ritual, procession, costuming and music to create a unique form of storied performance that unfolded in the plaza of the United Nations, New York.\n\n‘Ocean Calling’ is inspired by all forms of life that make the ocean their home, as well as by the people, the histories and the cosmography of the communities that for millennia have lived in close relationship with the ocean. The work unfolds in an urban environment highly dependent on the health of the oceans, even though it may not be overtly obvious to our urban communities. ‘Ocean Calling’ invited audiences to first acknowledge our intersecting identities and then, to celebrate and honor them by changing behaviors to protect our oceans.\n \nThe work also highlights the importance of the Declaration signed by Pacific Island Countries and Territories to significantly improve Ocean governance, which was drafted during the Pacific Regional Platform for Partnerships and Action on Sustainable Development Goal 14 (SDG14) meeting, which took place in 2017 in Suva, Fiji.\n \n‘Ocean Calling’ was developed in collaboration with artists from Mexico, Jamaica and the Caribbean diaspora. The first iteration of ‘Ocean Calling’ was presented in Jamaica as ‘What-Lives-Beneath’ in 2016 for TBA21–Academy’s ‘The Current I’ Convening ‘The Kula Ring’ led by Ute Meta Bauer.	\N	1	1	0	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	performance	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	t	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of Laura Anderson Barbata and TBA21–Academy	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	http://www.tba21oceanweek.org/oc	\N	\N	t	\N
