 currents collect and contain plastic from around the world. 'Plastic Reef' grew in size parallel to the increasing exposure and awareness that was slowly awakening. Every time the work was exhibited it became bigger as more and more plastic was added. In total more than 1000kg of plastic debris was fished out between 2008 and 2013. In 2015 scientists discovered that natural coral was ingesting micro-plastics, poisoning itself in the process. Next to acidification and water temperature rising, this is one of the main reasons for the disappearance of the Great Barrier Reef.	\N	1	1	1	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of the artist and Meessen De Clercq Gallery, Brussels	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	{2480,1654}	https://ocean-archive.org/collection/17	\N	\N	t	\N
