p://tba21.org/academy" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">TBA21–Academy’s</a> <a href="https://www.tba21.org/#item--the_current--1157" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">The Current</a> II Fellowship Programme:</p><p>‘It seems excessive to think of an animal that decides to negate its instinct and abandons hunting other animals or even humans ... even so, the idea fascinates me. I imagine that lion in the jungle, at ease, thoughtful, leaving behind, without a nostalgic hint, his time as a ferocious predator. I fantasise about the conversations he has with the lionesses (who were really the true hunters) and lions about the struggles of the past, the life battles that an accurate bite stopped at once. Ah! Now the rejoicing is another, hours of conversation with the gazelles ... what a world of theirs ...</p><p>Let us now think of another concept, that of “climate change”. This seems to be a change and thus the notion adds – almost positively – to a whole chain of other cultural changes, to all the changes that inevitably new times bring ... The media and the socio-political discourses use the term continuously without a note on its euphemistic character and how it denies the radical transformation that human activity imposes on the natural environment, on life.</p><p>I would like to add a second example: equity between individuals, even of individuals of a different species and genders, the possibility of achieving the simplest promise, that there is no trait that deserves any promotion or privilege in the realm of Life.</p><p>This expedition, through our being together, is about discussing the possibility of generating new habits and thinking about our activity, whatever the medium – art, education, writing or exhibitions – and based on an emotional and cognitive understanding of the challenges that the near future holds for us.’</p><p>– Chus Martínez</p>	\N	1	0	0	\N	\N	EN	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	