558	private/eu-central-1:12102e0b-bb96-42f0-9d3c-1df78ee120b2/418b7876-0b02-4d53-b0c4-38683f95c14b/16b15ac0-2327-11ea-9793-25a52dec1756-MHayes_Acid Immersion.pdf	cab8bd09465aaf2f00ce5622dbcd39d738b7b2d98c9092ba4961753ab82fa56e5e86691124caffe867bd743b5b7ce2cb3503a18248ab15c399b3fdace1c0d5bb	\N	\N	acf98f20faea9db896ffe15e3921ba58	\N	2019-12-20 23:49:11.248979+11	2019-12-20 23:53:11.668+11	\N	t	{2,3,8}	{1252,1253,124}	\N	{NL}	PDF	Essay	{"Megan Hayes"}	418b7876-0b02-4d53-b0c4-38683f95c14b	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	2019	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	CC BY-NC	Acid Immersion	\N	\N	About 1 million tons of carbon dioxide (CO2) are absorbed into the ocean every hour through surface waters, which act as a planetary sponge soaking up 30 percent of all CO2 in the atmosphere. As a consequence, the average pH of ocean surface water has dropped from 8.2 to 8.1 since the beginning of the industrial era—a 25 percent increase in acidity over the past two centuries, which is a rate not experienced in the last 55 million years. The form in which this chemical transition of ocean acidification unfolds can be thought in the terms of what Elizabeth Povinelli names the “quasi-event;” a slow, seeping state change occurring below technologically unmediated human modes of perception. Never directly rupturing the present, ocean acidification manifests instead as a low, corrosive hum of strain on the lives lived in these zones. Expressed across bodies, the corrosivity of this acid has appeared as many undoings, from the dissolve of shells to the biosemiotic scrambling of fish, but the expression of acidification is refracted by the terms of the arts and sciences. Building on field work undertaken with marine biologists at the Great Barrier Reef this essay will track the shifting chemistry of the hydrosphere as mediated by science, ecological theory, aesthetic form, and the marine bodies increasingly steeped in carbonic acid, and suggests an immersive analytic of acid to consider a planetary condition of dissolve.	\N	0	0	1	\N	\N	EN	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	f	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	Courtesy of Megan Hayes	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	\N	t	\N
